50|$|<b>Social</b> <b>accounting</b> for {{the purpose}} of {{management}} control is designed to support and facilitate the achievement of an organization's own objectives. Because <b>social</b> <b>accounting</b> is concerned with substantial self-reporting on a systemic level, individual reports are often referred to as social audits. The first complete internal model for <b>social</b> <b>accounting</b> and audit, 1981, was designed for social enterprises to help plan and measure their social, environmental and financial progress towards achieving their planned objectives.|$|E
